<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1093,1862]" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">
Ground color of body yellowish-green (
<figureCitation box="[646,729,1202,1226]" captionStart="FIGURES 58–61" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1976,1999]" captionTargetBox="[239,1350,1170,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-84@3.[229,1358,1167,1955]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 58–61. Empoasca (Empoasca) apibicruris, 58, head and thorax, dorsal view; 59, face; 60, whole body, lateral view; 61, whole body, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280491" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280491/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Fig. 61</figureCitation>
). Crown with distinct light green patch on each side of coronal suture (
<figureCitation box="[237,324,1238,1262]" captionStart="FIGURES 58–61" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1976,1999]" captionTargetBox="[239,1350,1170,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-84@3.[229,1358,1167,1955]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 58–61. Empoasca (Empoasca) apibicruris, 58, head and thorax, dorsal view; 59, face; 60, whole body, lateral view; 61, whole body, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280491" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280491/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Fig. 58</figureCitation>
). Eyes dark-brown. Pronotum with irregular yellow patches on anterior margin of pronotum and under eyes. Forewing and hindwing semitransparent. Abdomen yellow. Legs light yellow to green (
<figureCitation box="[1266,1350,1274,1298]" captionStart="FIGURES 58–61" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1976,1999]" captionTargetBox="[239,1350,1170,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-84@3.[229,1358,1167,1955]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 58–61. Empoasca (Empoasca) apibicruris, 58, head and thorax, dorsal view; 59, face; 60, whole body, lateral view; 61, whole body, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280491" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280491/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Fig. 60</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1093,1862]" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">
Ventral abdominal apodemes subparallel-sided, reaching segment 5 (
<figureCitation box="[941,1022,1309,1332]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–18" captionStartId="3.[151,263,1039,1062]" captionTargetBox="[200,1379,177,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-81@3.[151,1436,167,1018]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 10–18. Empoasca (Empoasca) apibicruris, 10, male pygofer, lateral view; 11, pygofer appendage; 12, abdominal apodemes; 13, anal tube appendage; 14, connective; 15, aedeagus, ventral view; 16, aedeagus, lateral view; 17, paramere; 18, subgenital plate." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280489/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Pygofer with short dorso-apical lobe curved mediad, posterior margin broadly rounded, ornamented with 8–9 rigid setae distributed from outer to inner face of pygofer (
<figureCitation box="[248,327,1379,1402]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–18" captionStartId="3.[151,263,1039,1062]" captionTargetBox="[200,1379,177,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-81@3.[151,1436,167,1018]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 10–18. Empoasca (Empoasca) apibicruris, 10, male pygofer, lateral view; 11, pygofer appendage; 12, abdominal apodemes; 13, anal tube appendage; 14, connective; 15, aedeagus, ventral view; 16, aedeagus, lateral view; 17, paramere; 18, subgenital plate." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280489/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
); pygofer appendage not exceeding pygofer margin, arcuate distally in lateral view, apex broadened and obliquely tapered (
<figureCitation box="[355,435,1413,1436]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–18" captionStartId="3.[151,263,1039,1062]" captionTargetBox="[200,1379,177,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-81@3.[151,1436,167,1018]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 10–18. Empoasca (Empoasca) apibicruris, 10, male pygofer, lateral view; 11, pygofer appendage; 12, abdominal apodemes; 13, anal tube appendage; 14, connective; 15, aedeagus, ventral view; 16, aedeagus, lateral view; 17, paramere; 18, subgenital plate." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280489/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Anal appendage stout, swollen distinctly in sub-apical part, narrowing and curved anterad apically (
<figureCitation box="[255,339,1448,1471]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–18" captionStartId="3.[151,263,1039,1062]" captionTargetBox="[200,1379,177,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-81@3.[151,1436,167,1018]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 10–18. Empoasca (Empoasca) apibicruris, 10, male pygofer, lateral view; 11, pygofer appendage; 12, abdominal apodemes; 13, anal tube appendage; 14, connective; 15, aedeagus, ventral view; 16, aedeagus, lateral view; 17, paramere; 18, subgenital plate." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280489/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate in lateral view curved gradually caudodorsad apically, expanded apically; with numerous macrosetae on apical half; dorsolateral margin group A with 4–5 long stout setae subbasally and group B with 22–23 short microsetae over apical 2/3 (
<figureCitation box="[590,671,1517,1540]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–18" captionStartId="3.[151,263,1039,1062]" captionTargetBox="[200,1379,177,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-81@3.[151,1436,167,1018]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 10–18. Empoasca (Empoasca) apibicruris, 10, male pygofer, lateral view; 11, pygofer appendage; 12, abdominal apodemes; 13, anal tube appendage; 14, connective; 15, aedeagus, ventral view; 16, aedeagus, lateral view; 17, paramere; 18, subgenital plate." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280489/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
). Paramere with 4 teeth on dentifer, 9–10 setae subapically, apex bent ventrad and blunt in lateral view, evenly tapered and curved laterad in ventral view (
<figureCitation box="[1043,1121,1552,1575]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–18" captionStartId="3.[151,263,1039,1062]" captionTargetBox="[200,1379,177,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-81@3.[151,1436,167,1018]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 10–18. Empoasca (Empoasca) apibicruris, 10, male pygofer, lateral view; 11, pygofer appendage; 12, abdominal apodemes; 13, anal tube appendage; 14, connective; 15, aedeagus, ventral view; 16, aedeagus, lateral view; 17, paramere; 18, subgenital plate." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280489/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
). Connective slightly broader than long, posterior margin medially emarginate, strongly sclerotized along mid-line but without obvious dorsal keel (
<figureCitation box="[159,241,1622,1645]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–18" captionStartId="3.[151,263,1039,1062]" captionTargetBox="[200,1379,177,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-81@3.[151,1436,167,1018]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 10–18. Empoasca (Empoasca) apibicruris, 10, male pygofer, lateral view; 11, pygofer appendage; 12, abdominal apodemes; 13, anal tube appendage; 14, connective; 15, aedeagus, ventral view; 16, aedeagus, lateral view; 17, paramere; 18, subgenital plate." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280489/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). Aedeagus shaft well sclerotized, unevenly tapered in lateral view; distal appendages slightly shorter than shaft, divergent at ca. 45º angle in posterior view; basal appendages slightly shorter than shaft, subparallel in ventral view (
<figureCitation box="[264,393,1694,1717]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–18" captionStartId="3.[151,263,1039,1062]" captionTargetBox="[200,1379,177,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-81@3.[151,1436,167,1018]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 10–18. Empoasca (Empoasca) apibicruris, 10, male pygofer, lateral view; 11, pygofer appendage; 12, abdominal apodemes; 13, anal tube appendage; 14, connective; 15, aedeagus, ventral view; 16, aedeagus, lateral view; 17, paramere; 18, subgenital plate." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280489/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Figs. 15, 16</figureCitation>
). Gonopore terminal.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="31" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1093,1862]" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1730,1754]" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Etymology:</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the combination “ 
<emphasis box="[974,1024,1731,1754]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">api–</emphasis>
” and “ 
<emphasis box="[1108,1197,1730,1754]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">bicruris</emphasis>
” which refers to the shape of apex shaft being furcated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="31" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1093,1862]" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,1801,1826]" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
The new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Dworakowska, 1977 b" authorityName="Dworakowska" authorityYear="1977" box="[661,1157,1802,1826]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Empoasca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albipennis">
<emphasis box="[661,901,1802,1826]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Empoasca albipennis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Dworakowska" box="[908,1157,1802,1826]" firstAuthor="Dworakowska" pageId="2" pageNumber="31" pagination="9 - 47" refId="ref3855" refString="Dworakowska, I. (1977 b) On some Typhlocybinae from Vietnam (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). Folia Entomologica Hungarica, 30 (2), 9 - 47." type="journal article" year="1977" yearSuffix="b">Dworakowska, 1977b</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs in having the two pairs of processes short and the pygofer appendage not forked.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
